  <!-- BACK BOILER SECTION — UNIQUE ST HELENS CONTENT -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">ST HELENS SPECIALIST SERVICE</span>
      <h2>Back Boiler Servicing in St Helens. A Different Job Entirely.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">St Helens has more back boilers per square mile than almost anywhere else in Merseyside. Many WA10 Victorian terraces still run heating and hot water from a back boiler behind the gas fire in the living room. Servicing them correctly is not the same as servicing a combi.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-red">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Why Back Boilers Need Specialist Servicing</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Back boilers operate with a heat exchanger in a confined space, typically within the chimney breast. Unlike a wall-mounted combi, heat exchanger access during the service requires removal of the gas fire or access panel, and the flue path runs internally through the chimney before exiting at the roof rather than through a short external wall flue. This creates several specific service requirements: the flue baffle within the boiler must be checked and repositioned if displaced, the draught diverter must be tested to confirm it is opening and closing correctly, the open flue integrity must be confirmed through a combustion spillage test and any debris in the heat exchanger must be cleared. An engineer who primarily services combi boilers and treats a back boiler as a standard job will miss several of these checks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">The Carbon Monoxide Risk in Back Boiler Properties</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Back boilers in older WA10 properties are associated with a higher carbon monoxide risk than modern sealed-flue boilers for a specific reason. An open flue back boiler relies on the natural draught within the chimney to draw combustion gases upward and out of the property. If the chimney becomes partially blocked, if the draught diverter fails to open under high-flow conditions, or if the heat exchanger develops micro-cracks, products of combustion including carbon monoxide can spill into the room. This spillage can happen without any obvious sign and is why the combustion spillage test at the annual service is not optional. We carry out this test as standard on every back boiler service in St Helens.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-green">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Gas Fire Servicing on the Same Visit</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Many WA10 properties with back boilers still have the original gas fire in place, either in active use or decorative. The gas fire must be included in the annual gas safety inspection and service. We service gas fires on the same visit as the boiler service at no additional labour cost — just the charge for any additional parts if required. For landlords, this is particularly important: the CP12 gas safety certificate must cover all gas appliances in the property, and an uninspected gas fire means the CP12 is incomplete regardless of the boiler's condition.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


